title: For Sale/Trade:  IMI Desert Eagle Mark I .44 Magnum
postcontent:
I picked up this cannon at the last Goodman show on a whim, but I've decided to move it along. The pistol is a 1986-era Mark I .44 magnum model with the original cardboard box, magazine, and little tools that were included in the box. Mag is marked 2-86. Also included are three more mags, two of them are factory IMI(one marked 7-95 and one marked 7-08), and one is a ProMag clone. I have 20 rounds of MagTech 240gr. JSP and 24rds of PMC 240gr. TCSP left after the range session last weekend, and both brands run reliably in the D.E..

The gun is in great mechanical condition but has some typical finish wear on it for an almost 30-year old gun. There is no rust but the edges, front of the grip, and high spots are thin, and the finish has that slight purplish-tone that they all get after a few years. The bore is a mirror and the internals are clean and show little wear.  It's a reliable blaster and a lot of fun to shoot. The three factory mags are 100% reliable, the ProMag isn't if loaded with more than five rounds, so consider it a 'gimme'.

title: For Sale:  Colt LE901 -16S 901 .308 Carbine w/ Conversion Kit
postcontent:
This Colt LE901 with the Adapter Block Conversion Kit is the older version. The newer versions are being sold by Colt WITHOUT the LE901 Adapter Block Conversion Kit and they are making the kit available for purchase separately.
Be it prairie dog hunting in Texas, whitetail hunting in Maine or elk hunting in Colorado, the Colt LE901-16S™ is the rifle for the hunt. At first glance you would think that the Colt 901 is just a .308 Win./7.62 NATO version of a standard AR-15, much like any other .308 AR out there, but it is a lot more than that. The Colt LE901-16S is a “Modular Carbine,” which means it can be adapted to any AR-15 platform upper. This isn’t a new concept, because there are of course a whole bunch of different caliber uppers for ARs. The difference is in all the other ones, they have adapted a standard size AR magazine to boutique calibers and cartridge designs. The Colt 901 is different. It can be adapted from .308/7.62, using standard P-Mags, to .223/5.56, using standard AR mags, and back again, in literally seconds. The design uses one proprietary part, and you have to swap out the recoil system. It is that simple, and it works fantastic .

postcontent:
The original PTR rifle was first conceived in 2002, when a predecessor company purchased tooling and designs for the HK line of roller-lock weapons from Fabrica Militar of Portugal. Initially, small quantities HK-91 “clone” rifles were produced, mostly from surplus parts acquired around the world. From 2002-2006, the reputation of the PTR-91 rifle grew considerably along with the market for it. PTR was organized in 2006 to meet that demand. Over the next few years, the company consistently grew its capabilities. Expanding beyond the original 91 “clone”, PTR began to introduce many other models and variants to suit different shooting applications. Today the company is known affectionately as just “PTR”, due to the fact that the product offerings have expanded well beyond the original PTR-91 rifle.
